-- China Stocks: Dongfang Electric, Fangda Carbon, Shanghai Maling
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2010-12-20T07:47:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-19/bank-of-china-citic-securities-construction-bank-china-equities-preview.html
The  Shanghai Composite Index , which
tracks the bigger of China’s stock exchanges, dropped 40.83, or
1.4 percent, to 2,852.92 at the 3 p.m. close. The  CSI 300 Index 
retreated 1.5 percent to 3,178.66. Stock symbols are in
parentheses after company names.  Drugmakers:  Kangmei Pharmaceutical Co.  (600518 CH) lost 4.6
percent to 21.15 yuan. Beijing Tiantan Biological Products Corp.
(600161 CH) retreated 2.8 percent to 23.22 yuan while North
China Pharmaceutical Co. (600812 CH) dropped 2.6 percent to
16.46 yuan. A gauge of health-care stocks tumbled 3 percent, the
most among the 10 industry groups on the CSI 300 Index.  The National Development and Reform Commission may lower
prices by an average 40 percent for 658 approved medications,
the Economic Observer reported today, citing officials from
unidentified pharmaceuticals companies. The NDRC didn’t
immediately respond to a fax seeking comment.  Dongfang Electric Corp.  (600875 CH), China’s third-largest
power equipment maker, advanced 2.5 percent to 35.10 yuan, the
highest since Nov. 11. The company said it received 20.4 billion
yuan ($3.06 billion) of orders for thermal-, wind- and nuclear-
power generating equipment from India and China.  Fangda Carbon New Material Co.  (600516 CH) climbed 5
percent to 13.59 yuan, a record since its listing in 2002. The
stock was raised to “buy” by Citic Securities Co. analysts
 Zhou Xizeng  and  Li Hongliang , who cited increasing demand for
carbon bricks from the photovoltaic and nuclear industries. The
brokerage set a share-price estimate of 18 yuan.  Shanghai Maling Aquarius Co.  (600073 CH), a manufacturer of
canned food, jumped the 10 percent daily limit to 14.32 yuan
after saying it plans to buy 1.55 billion yuan of assets from
its parent. Shanghai Maling will issue as many as 134.2 million
shares at no less than 11.55 yuan each to pay for the assets.
The stock resumed trading after being suspended since Nov. 29.       Tianjin Port Co.  (600717 CH), a port operator, slid 2.9
percent to 8.44 yuan after saying 579.5 million of its locked-up
shares would become tradable on Dec. 27.  -- Zhang Shidong . Editor:  Allen Wan   To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
